    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "got it. so essentially the resistance is the steady part and the reactance is the part that's fighting the current more dynamically. can u explain why the reactance specifically acts as a form of resistance to the current flow in an inductor? like what is actually happening physically to create that impedance?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Physically, the inductive reactance arises because inductors resist *changes* in current flow, not steady current itself. When current tries to change in an inductor, the magnetic field it generates creates a back electromotive force (EMF) that opposes that change. This opposition to the *rate* of current change is what we model mathematically as reactance, which behaves similarly to resistance in determining the circuit's total opposition to AC currents.",
      "source": "target",
